Saturday, January 24, 1942

Worked all day on correlations; finished the Pituophis calculations.

Breeze reports a small banded King in Mission Gorge eating a skink. Was out in the open.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 02/16/2012 12:14 PM

Sunday, January 25, 1942

Worked all day on correlations (except out to lunch) and finished the first draft of the scale correlations -- harmless snakes. Over 60 of these took many weeks.

Shaw finished the counts on the 1941 snakes today.

Thursday, January 29, 1942

Saw Slevin in SF for a couple of hours in the afternoon and measured the overall lengths of the Laguna Island Sonora m. linearis.

Notes:

lwilliams

Sonora m. linearis = Thamnophis melanogaster ???

Sunday, February 22, 1942

Spent all day and evening on miscellaneous filing and recording in which I have been behind for a year or more, while writing papers. Must get some of this up to date as it is beginning to interfere with other work. Will keep this up for several days.

Sunday, March 1, 1942

Shaw and some of his friends went out to Boulder Creek today in my car for some Triturus for Myers.

I spent the entire day and evening transferring last years colubrid counts to the large books and got about 2/3 finished. A tedious but necessary job.

Julius funeral today.

Saturday, March 14, 1942

Spent the entire day on 1941 records - particularly the S.D. Co census. this is now up to date as far as the entry sheets are concerned. The summaries ave not been drawn off for the last 3 years, but this is only a matter of bookkeeping. At least the data are readily available anytime.

Saturday, March 21, 1942

Spent the entire day on the necessary drudgery of tabulating last years trip records. Hate to take this time from original work but it seems necessary.

Can now return to the correlation studies which I dropped on Feb. 1.

Got started on the correlation paper again today after 6 weeks on filing and records. Mad some progress - not too good. Calculations are painfully slow and voluminous.

Monday, May 11, 1942

As I was due in Los Angeles for a business meeting tomorrow, I went via the Mojave for what may be the only snake hunt of the year. Started at 3:30 pm (Pacific War Time). Warm, windy and part cloudy.

1 Red Racer L DOR El Toro grass Blackhead
1 gopher S L DOR El Toro Grass Saved
San Bernardino at 7 pm. Cold cloudy and windy. The outlook bad.
Adelanto at 7:55. Cold and Windy. Sundown at 7:45 pm
Kramer Junction at 8:55 pm very cold and windy 52 degrees. Seeing there was no change to get anything we drove fast from here on reaching LA at midnight.

Total miles today 329 mi
Evening drive 1 hour (Adelanto to Kramer Junction) 29 miles

Saturday, May 23, 1942

A day of small accomplishment having got badly stuck on two mathematical items namely the test for linearity and the significance of the constant term in the body-tail equation. Decided to elaborate on the tail to body length relationship in the correlations paper, which led to the above results.

Sunday, June 1, 1942

Arrived at Chicago; departed for Washington.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 02/16/2012 04:37 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/14/2012 04:31 PM

Monday, June 8, 1942

Arrived at Washington at 8:40. Took quite a while checking baggage and buying tickets. Then went to the USNM where I met Miss Cochran. Talked specimens, and statistics. Visited Dr. Stejneger for an hour or more and discussed the possibility of Cope's Chilomeniscus ephippicus coming from California. Wonderful how the old gentleman (now nearing 91) remembers all the notes and lines of investigation. I asked him particularly about the Baird and Girard ms to accompany the Pacific RR report, but he didn't know where it could be.

Went to the U.S. Nat. Gallery of Art for lunch. Waited a long time for a chance to eat.

Then back to the USNM until 5 pm checking a few snakes and snake lists.

Left for NY at 6 pm and arrived at 10.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 02/16/2012 04:46 PM
  • Mary Miller 02/14/2012 04:36 PM
  • BPOC 12/21/2010 01:15 PM

Tuesday, June 9, 1942

Went to the AMNH a few moments after 9 and stayed until 5:15. Saw Bogert's work on teeth on cobras (especially teeth) and on Salvadora. He has many wonderful drawings. Met Jas. Oliver also later in the afternoon, Mrs. Clifford Pope. The entire day was spent in the discussion of problems and statistics, and was most interesting.
Took lunch with the staff and met G.G. Simpson. After lunch went to Simpson's office and discussed statistics. Met Mont. Cazier an entomologist with whom I had corresponded. Then back to Bogert's office for more discussion and argument.

Also met Hefetz the man who overhauled Uma.

A very worthwhile day.

1 C. cerastes L DOR 2 mi W. of Coyote Wells
1 P.d. perkinsi S DOR Coyote Wells
1 P.c.deserticola S DOR Coyote Wells
1 P.c. deserticola 4 mi E. of Coyote Wells

Drove from foot of Mt. Springs grade at 9:20 pm 92 degrees to Yuma at 1:20 pm MWT. 90 miles. Nothing seen alive. 90 degrees at El Centro, 88 degrees at Haltville ( 11 pm) Cool at Yuma

------------------------

Friday, September 11, 1942

Shaw and Breeze Trip

1 Patchnose S DOR 10 mi NE of Nogales mesquite and grassy bush
1 T. eques M DOR 14 mi NE of Nogales grass hills and oaks
1 T. eques M AOR 14 mi NE of Nogales 10:00 79 degrees Escaped
Caught a P.s. affinis under a large rock warm and clear 10:30 am. Snake cold and lethargic 6 mi SW of Patagonia, Santa Cruz.

Hunted at a stream paralleling the road.
3 mi SW of Patagonia got 3 Rana pipiens. Also a Coluber semilineatus under a large flat rock lying on the ground. 11:40 am warm and overcast very 'muggy'
2 mi SW of Patagonia, stopped to turn over some logs. Got a small P.s. affinis under a large rotten log in the pasture 11:55 am
1 Salvadora L DOR 1 1/2 mi SW of Patagonia mesquite
1 Salvadora s DOR 1 mi SW of Patagonia Saved
Patagonia 12 mi 81 degrees
1 C.f. piceus (red phase) 7 mi N. of Patagonia L DOR Cottonwoods and mesquite. Very large-light red all over. Being eaten by buzzards.
Kinosternon sonoriense St. David DOR Pond
1 Salvadora 1 mi W. of St. David S DOR Saved mesquite

Returned to Tucson at 7:12 88 degrees
(continued on Sept. 6th)

Saturday, September 19, 1942

Spent the entire day working up the tai length statistics on gloyds 2 series and Loveridges 4. As usual wasted much time running down errors. These were not yet finished, but the worst is probably over. As of this date I am down to the standard errors of estimate on all the other series.

Lampropeltis getula

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
